GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 316
Short Title: Child Care Act. (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives Logan, G. Brown, Lopez, and G. Pierce (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Rules, Calendar, and Operations of the House
March 10, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO REENACT THE NORTH CAROLINA CHILD TAX CREDIT, TO EXPAND
3 THE NORTH CAROLINA PREKINDERGARTEN (NC PRE-K) PROGRAM AND
4 INCREASE CARE SUBSIDY BY APPROPRIATING FUNDS FOR THOSE PURPOSES,
5 TO PROVIDE LUNCH IN PUBLIC SCHOOLS AT NO COST TO STUDENTS
6 THROUGH AN ALLOCATION BASED ON SCHOOL FOOD AUTHORITY
7 EVALUATIONS, TO APPROPRIATE FUNDS FOR PUBLIC CHILD CARE PROVIDED
8 BY COMMUNITY COLLEGES, AND TO REQUIRE A REPORT ON THE FEASIBILITY
9 AND ADVISABILITY OF A HIGH SCHOOL CHILD CARE APPRENTICESHIP
10 PROGRAM.
11 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
12
13 PART I. NC CHILD TAX CREDIT
14 SECTION 1.1. G.S. 105-151.11 is reenacted as it existed immediately before its
15 expiration, is recodified as G.S. 105-153.12, and reads as rewritten:
16 "§ 105-153.12. Credit for child care and certain employment-related expenses.
17 (a) Credit. – A person who is allowed a credit against federal income tax for a percentage
18 of employment-related expenses under section 21 of the Code shall be allowed as a credit against
19 the tax imposed by this Part an amount equal to the applicable percentage of the
20 employment-related expenses as defined in section 21(b)(2) of the Code. In order to claim the
21 credit allowed by this section, the taxpayer must provide with the tax return the information
22 required by the Secretary.
23 (a1) Applicable Percentage. – For employment-related expenses that are incurred only
24 with respect to one or more dependents who are seven 18 years old or older up to 25 years old
25 and are not physically or mentally incapable of caring for themselves, the applicable percentage
26 is the appropriate percentage in the column labeled "Percentage A" in the table below, based on
27 the taxpayer's adjusted gross income determined under the Code. For employment-related
28 expenses that are incurred only with respect to one or more dependents who are 12 years old up
29 to 18 years old and are not physically or mentally incapable of caring for themselves, the
30 applicable percentage is the appropriate percentage in the column labeled "Percentage B" in the
31 table below, based on the taxpayer's adjusted gross income determined under the Code. For
32 employment-related expenses that are incurred only with respect to one or more dependents who
33 are 6 years old up to 12 years old and are not physically or mentally incapable of caring for
34 themselves, the applicable percentage is the appropriate percentage in the column labeled
35 "Percentage C" in the table below, based on the taxpayer's adjusted gross income determined
