3
4 PART II. EXPAND NC PRE-K PROGRAM
5 SECTION 2.1. There is appropriated from the General Fund to the Department of
6 Health and Human Services, Division of Child Development and Early Education, the sum of
7 two hundred million dollars ($200,000,000) in recurring funds for each year of the 2025-2027
8 fiscal biennium for the North Carolina Prekindergarten (NC Pre-K) program to expand the
9 number of slots by 32,000 and cover all eligible children 4 years of age.
10
11 PART III. INCREASE SUBSIDIZED CHILD CARE FUNDING
12 SECTION 3.1. There is appropriated from the General Fund to the Department of
13 Health and Human Services, Division of Child Development and Early Education, the sum of
14 thirty-five million dollars ($35,000,000) in recurring funds for each year of the 2025-2027 fiscal
15 biennium to increase funding for subsidized child care.
16
17 PART IV. FUND PUBLIC SCHOOL LUNCHES
18 SECTION 4.1. G.S. 115C-263 reads as rewritten:
19 "§ 115C-263. School nutrition services.
20 (a) As a part of the function of the public school system, local boards of education public
21 school units shall have a school food authority to provide to the extent practicable school nutrition
22 services in the schools under their jurisdiction. jurisdiction by offering students lunch at no cost
23 to the student. A school food authority may offer students a breakfast option at a cost to the
24 student, unless the student is eligible for the School Breakfast Program. All school nutrition
25 services made available under this authority shall be provided in accordance with federal
26 guidelines established by the Food and Nutrition Service of the United States Department of
27 Agriculture.
28 (b) The To the extent that funds are made available for the purpose, the State Board of
29 Education shall allocate funds to school food authorities at public school units for the purpose of
30 providing healthy lunches at no cost to students. In issuing the allocation, the Board shall do the
31 following:
32 (1) Determine the amount to allocate to each school food authority based on an
33 evaluation of the authority's nutrition services. The Board shall develop the
34 method and criteria for the evaluation, which at a minimum shall account for
35 the following:
36 a. The size of the schools served by the school food authority as
37 determined by Average Daily Membership.
38 b. The number of students that are eligible for free or reduced-price lunch
39 and the estimated receipts from the National School Lunch Program.
40 c. The funds actually expended in the prior year, which may be waived
41 if the school food authority was not in operation in the year prior.
42 d. The extent to which the nutrition services promote health and wellness
43 by providing food that is of high quality and nutrient content.
44 e. The extent to which the school food authority uses locally sourced
45 food and products.
46 f. Any other information the Board deems relevant to the cost and
47 operation of the nutrition services.
48 (2) Ensure the funds are distributed on a fair and equitable basis.
49 (3) Issue the allocation at the beginning of each fiscal year, except that the Board
50 may reserve for future allocation a reasonable amount, not to exceed ten
51 percent (10%) of the total funds available for providing nutrition services.
