1 (c) The State Board of Education may adopt rules regulating the provision of school
2 nutrition that impose additional restrictions that are not inconsistent with the federal guidelines.
3 (d) Funds allocated pursuant to this section shall supplement and not supplant any other
4 funds from any other source provided for the same purpose."
5 SECTION 4.2. G.S. 115C-264(a) reads as rewritten:
6 "(a) Local boards of education operating school nutrition programs shall participate in the
7 federal National School Lunch Program established by the federal government. and, if eligible,
8 the Community Eligibility Provision Program. School nutrition programs shall be under the
9 jurisdiction of the Division of School Nutrition of the Department of Public Instruction."
10 SECTION 4.3 G.S. 115C-218.75 is amended by adding a new subsection to read:
11 "(p) A charter school shall provide school nutrition services in accordance with
12 G.S. 115C-263 and G.S. 115C-264."
13 SECTION 4.4. G.S. 115C-238.72(b) reads as rewritten:
14 "(b) Food Nutrition Service. – The local school administrative unit identified by resolution
15 shall provide, to the extent practicable, school food provide school nutrition services to the
16 regional school. school in accordance with G.S. 115C-263 and G.S. 115C-264. For purposes of
17 federal funding through the National School Lunch Program or other federally supported food
18 nutrition service programs, the local school administrative unit identified by resolution shall be
19 permitted to include eligible students enrolled in the regional school. Other participating units
20 shall not include students enrolled in the regional school for purposes of federally supported food
21 nutrition service programs."
22 SECTION 4.5. G.S. 115C-150.14 is amended by adding a new subsection to read:
23 "(a1) A school governed by this Article shall provide school nutrition services in
24 accordance with G.S. 115C-263 and G.S. 115C-264."
25 SECTION 4.6. G.S. 116-239.8(b)(4)c. reads as rewritten:
26 "c. Food Nutrition Services. – The laboratory school shall strive to ensure
27 that one hundred percent (100%) muscadine grape juice is made
28 available to students as a part of the school's nutrition program or
29 through the operation of the school's vending facilities. Laboratory
30 schools shall provide school nutrition services in accordance with
31 G.S. 115C-263 and G.S. 115C-264. Upon request, the local school
32 administrative unit in which the laboratory school is located shall
33 administer the National School Lunch Program for the laboratory
34 school in accordance with G.S. 115C-264.school."
35 SECTION 4.7. There is appropriated from the General Fund to the Department of
36 Public Instruction the sum of one hundred fifteen million dollars ($115,000,000) in recurring
37 funds for the 2025-2026 fiscal year to provide lunch to students in public school units at no cost
38 to the students in accordance with this section. Should this appropriation not be sufficient to
39 fulfill the provisions of this section for the 2025-2026 fiscal year, the State Board of Education
40 may use funds appropriated to State Aid for Public Schools for this purpose.
41 SECTION 4.8. There is appropriated from the General Fund to the Department of
42 Public Instruction the sum of three million one hundred sixty-six thousand six hundred dollars
43 ($3,166,600) in nonrecurring funds for the 2025-2026 fiscal year to satisfy any outstanding
44 school nutrition program debt. Should this appropriation not be sufficient to satisfy all school
45 nutrition program debt by the end of the 2025-2026 fiscal year, the State Board of Education
46 shall use funds appropriated to State Aid for Public Schools for this purpose.
47 SECTION 4.9. The State Board of Education is granted authority to adopt temporary
48 rules to enact this section until permanent rules are adopted.
49
50 PART V. FUNDS FOR PUBLIC CHILD CARE PROVIDED BY COMMUNITY
51 COLLEGES
Page 4 House Bill 316-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 SECTION 5.1. Appropriation. – There is appropriated from the General Fund to the
2 Community Colleges System Office the sum of ten million dollars ($10,000,000) in nonrecurring
3 funds for the 2025-2026 fiscal year to be allocated in accordance with this section among
4 community colleges with an active child care program that is available to the public to support
5 and maintain that program. The State Board of Community Colleges shall adopt a formula for
6 allocating these funds. Funds shall be allocated based on the number of children served by the
7 program, and the State Board shall prioritize the award of funds based on the financial needs of
8 the program. These funds shall not revert at the end of the 2025-2026 fiscal year but shall remain
9 available until expended.
10 SECTION 5.2. Report. – Any community college that does not have a publicly
11 available child care program shall report to the State Board of Community Colleges on the
12 feasibility and advisability of implementing a publicly available child care program at that
13 community college, including recommendations for implementing such a child care program,
14 estimated costs, and barriers to implementation. The State Board shall aggregate that information
15 and report it to the Joint Legislative Education Oversight Committee no later than March 31,
16 2026.
17
18 PART VI. REPORT ON HIGH SCHOOL CHILD CARE APPRENTICESHIP
19 PROGRAM
20 SECTION 6.1. No later than December 31, 2026, the Department of Public
21 Instruction, in consultation with each partner agency, shall report to the Joint Legislative
22 Education Oversight Committee on the feasibility and advisability of implementing a child care
23 apprenticeship program in public high schools. The report shall include at least the following
24 information:
25 (1) Estimated costs and a time line for implementing a statewide or regional child
26 care apprenticeship program.
27 (2) Expected student and community impacts of a child care apprenticeship
28 program, including impacts on student performance, attrition, well-being, and
29 any other factor the Department deems relevant to the report.
30 SECTION 6.2. No later than February 28, 2027, the Joint Legislative Education
31 Oversight Committee shall hold a committee meeting and receive an in-person presentation from
32 the Department, in partnership with each partner agency, on the report provided pursuant to
33 Section 6.1 of this act.
34 SECTION 6.3. For purposes of this section, the term "partner agency" shall refer to
35 the Department of Health and Human Services, the Board of Governors of The University of
36 North Carolina, and the State Board of Community Colleges.
37
38 PART VII. EFFECTIVE DATE
39 SECTION 7.1. Part I of this act is effective for taxable years beginning on or after
40 January 1, 2025. The remainder of this act becomes effective July 1, 2025.
